They're getting all the couriers.

255
00:33:54,533 --> 00:33:59,370
Please could you tell me,
Boss Tweed, around 1875...

256
00:33:59,955 --> 00:34:02,957
Boss, is that his name? Boss?

257
00:34:03,375 --> 00:34:06,544
No, that's his nickname.
William Marcy Tweed.

258
00:34:06,629 --> 00:34:09,297
- Marthy...
- I'll write it down for you.

259
00:34:13,219 --> 00:34:19,724
They called him Boss,
because he was a corrupt politician.

260
00:34:20,309 --> 00:34:25,396
He had a bunch of political hacks
called "the Tweed ring".

261
00:34:25,481 --> 00:34:27,315
This I know. Thank you.

262
00:34:27,399 --> 00:34:29,734
- Could I have the pencil, please?
- It's mine.

263
00:35:14,446 --> 00:35:15,446
(HONKING)

264
00:35:21,370 --> 00:35:22,870
Miss Opel!

265
00:35:26,125 --> 00:35:27,458
Miss Opel!

266
00:35:29,211 --> 00:35:32,547
Miss Opel. Hi. Sorry.

267
00:35:34,466 --> 00:35:38,219
You forgot your book.
I thought it might be important.

268
00:35:38,304 --> 00:35:40,847
- Thank you. Bye.
- Bye.

269
00:35:42,141 --> 00:35:46,060
Your name and address
were on the inside of it,

270
00:35:46,145 --> 00:35:49,564
in case you were wondering
how I knew where you live.

271
00:35:49,648 --> 00:35:51,399
I wasn't.

272
00:35:52,067 --> 00:35:54,569
- Thank you again. Bye.
- Bye.

273
00:35:56,405 --> 00:35:57,572
Goodbye.

274
00:35:58,490 --> 00:35:59,574
Bye.

275
00:36:01,910 --> 00:36:04,329
You say "good night", but you don't go.

276
00:36:04,413 --> 00:36:08,249
I twisted my ankle on the way.
I was hoping to rest it.

277
00:36:08,334 --> 00:36:11,336
- But you're not limping.
- I'm a marathon runner.

278
00:36:11,420 --> 00:36:14,255
When you race 26 miles,
you don't give in to pain.

279
00:36:14,340 --> 00:36:18,760
- It hurts, but I don't pay any attention.
- You won at this?

280
00:36:18,844 --> 00:36:22,597
I haven't run a whole marathon yet,
but I hope to.

281
00:36:22,681 --> 00:36:25,683
I wish you good luck. Bye.

282
00:36:26,518 --> 00:36:29,270
- I'm sorry I stole your book.
- What?

283
00:36:29,355 --> 00:36:32,607
I took your book.
I didn't know how to talk to you.

284
00:36:32,691 --> 00:36:34,942
I was embarrassed, so I took your book.

285
00:36:35,027 --> 00:36:38,446
- Aren't you embarrassed now?
- Yeah, I'm humiliated.

286
00:36:38,530 --> 00:36:41,407
Why do you pursue people
who sit at your library table?

287
00:36:41,492 --> 00:36:45,286
I don't. It's just that you're pretty.

288
00:36:47,623 --> 00:36:52,627
I can't talk about how smart you are.
I don't know you. I'm done lying.

289
00:36:52,711 --> 00:36:55,380
Are you always
so incompetent with women?

290
00:36:55,464 --> 00:36:59,884
- Today is above average for me.
- Congratulations. Good night.

291
00:36:59,968 --> 00:37:02,970
That's too bad.
I could make you so happy.

292
00:37:03,055 --> 00:37:04,138
I'm smart as a whip.

293
00:37:04,223 --> 00:37:07,058
You won't meet
another thief like me in a library.

294
00:37:07,142 --> 00:37:09,435
Why don't you say you'll see me? Huh?

295
00:37:09,978 --> 00:37:13,147
- All right. I'll see you again.
- (PHONE RINGING)

296
00:37:13,857 --> 00:37:15,566
But it won't come to anything.

297
00:37:15,651 --> 00:37:16,984
You can't tell.

298
00:37:18,654 --> 00:37:19,987
Yes, I can.

299
00:38:04,283 --> 00:38:05,783
(TOLLING LOUDLY)

300
00:38:10,706 --> 00:38:12,039
(CHATTERING)

301
00:38:22,384 --> 00:38:23,843
(OPERA PLAYING)

302
00:38:40,110 --> 00:38:41,903
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

303
00:38:45,073 --> 00:38:46,991
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

304
00:40:40,105 --> 00:40:42,857
- How do you say "seals" in French?
- Phoques.

305
00:40:42,941 --> 00:40:46,527
So you look at the phoque?
How do you spell that?

306
00:40:46,612 --> 00:40:49,196
- You don't believe it.
- How do you spell it?

307
00:40:49,281 --> 00:40:51,616
- F-O-C.
- No "K"?

308
00:40:53,160 --> 00:40:54,327
(CLANGING LOUDLY)

309
00:40:55,495 --> 00:40:57,872
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

310
00:40:59,583 --> 00:41:00,875
(TUNE PLAYING)

311
00:41:07,716 --> 00:41:09,050
I like you.

312
00:41:10,385 --> 00:41:12,136
I like you, too.

313
00:41:12,346 --> 00:41:15,222
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

314
00:41:20,479 --> 00:41:22,688
- Merde.
- I know.

315
00:41:37,996 --> 00:41:41,290
- What's the time?
- 11:47. You're faster.

316
00:41:41,375 --> 00:41:43,501
- It's 'cause of you.
- Come on. Lunch!

317
00:41:43,585 --> 00:41:45,586
- One more!
- Oh, no!

318
00:42:19,413 --> 00:42:20,621
(PANTING)

319
00:42:21,456 --> 00:42:24,375
No, Babe. Not again.

320
00:42:27,546 --> 00:42:28,796
Come on.

321
00:42:32,384 --> 00:42:34,051
I can't!

322
00:42:44,146 --> 00:42:46,147
Neither can I.

323
00:42:48,483 --> 00:42:50,151
Thank God!

324
00:43:13,675 --> 00:43:15,551
Come on.

325
00:43:33,695 --> 00:43:35,112
BABE: What?

326
00:43:35,197 --> 00:43:37,615
ELSA: Babe! Babe.

327
00:43:39,117 --> 00:43:40,367
Babe!

328
00:43:40,660 --> 00:43:42,703
(GRUNTING)

329
00:43:58,345 --> 00:43:59,678
Babe!

330
00:44:04,142 --> 00:44:07,812
BABE: "Dear, Doc,
I don't feel much like writing,

331
00:44:07,896 --> 00:44:10,147
"too torn apart, I guess,

332
00:44:10,232 --> 00:44:13,776
"but maybe I ought to tell you
something about Elsa Opel.

333
00:44:14,653 --> 00:44:15,653
"I met her recently.

334
00:44:15,737 --> 00:44:19,073
"She's a history student.
I think she's Swiss.

335
00:44:20,325 --> 00:44:24,662
"In a sense, I guess
we are what you might call smitten.

336
00:44:24,746 --> 00:44:27,248
"Maybe I should tell you what happened.

337
00:44:27,332 --> 00:44:30,668
"We were in Central Park one night.
We stayed too late.

338
00:44:30,752 --> 00:44:33,838
"You were right about this town,
'cause we finally got mugged.

339
00:44:33,922 --> 00:44:35,089
"It's a funny thing.

340
00:44:35,173 --> 00:44:39,009
"You always talk about
how I don't confront things.

341
00:44:39,094 --> 00:44:41,679
"But I feel like if
I could find those guys,

342
00:44:41,763 --> 00:44:46,016
"for the first time I feel like I could,
maybe I could kill them.

343
00:44:46,101 --> 00:44:50,020
"It's funny, 'cause I never knew
I could feel like that inside.

344
00:44:50,522 --> 00:44:54,358
"So what else is there to say?
There's nothing else new here.

345
00:44:54,526 --> 00:44:57,528
"Reach me if you can. Babe."

346
00:45:09,916 --> 00:45:12,042
(MAN SPEAKING SPANISH OVER PA)

347
00:45:29,311 --> 00:45:32,980
Ladies and gentlemen,
we have news, unfortunately,

348
00:45:33,064 --> 00:45:37,818
that there's been no solution
to the strike at Kennedy Airport.

349
00:45:37,903 --> 00:45:41,113
We trust this won't cause you
too great an inconvenience

350
00:45:41,197 --> 00:45:44,783
and that you will once again fly with us.
Muchas gracias.

351
00:45:49,080 --> 00:45:52,082
WOMAN: (OVER PA) Will passengers
who have identified their baggage

352
00:45:52,167 --> 00:45:54,752
please go to customs?

353
00:46:00,467 --> 00:46:01,842
(MAN LAUGHING)

354
00:46:28,662 --> 00:46:29,870
(INAUDIBLE)

355
00:46:40,048 --> 00:46:41,757
The land of plenty.

356
00:46:42,801 --> 00:46:45,803
They were always so confident
God was on their side.

357
00:46:45,887 --> 00:46:48,472
- Now, I think they are not so sure.
- (LAUGHS)

358
00:46:55,814 --> 00:46:57,064
(DOOR OPENS)

359
00:47:02,195 --> 00:47:03,529
(DOOR CLOSES)

360
00:47:20,880 --> 00:47:22,131
(THUDDING)

361
00:47:25,593 --> 00:47:27,428
Who's there?

362
00:47:27,762 --> 00:47:29,346
Who is it?

363
00:47:33,435 --> 00:47:34,935
I got a gun.

364
00:47:36,271 --> 00:47:37,771
I got a gun.

365
00:47:43,319 --> 00:47:44,737
(MUFFLED SHOUTING)

366
00:47:48,033 --> 00:47:52,536
- Articulate as always.
- Prick. You scared the shit out of me.

367
00:47:52,620 --> 00:47:53,662
(CHUCKLES)

368
00:47:53,747 --> 00:47:56,915
- What time is it?
- Don't know. Must be about midnight.

369
00:47:57,000 --> 00:48:00,377
- Why didn't you say you were coming?
- I wanted to test your reflexes.

370
00:48:00,462 --> 00:48:02,713
- Still challenging me?
- As always.

371
00:48:02,797 --> 00:48:05,924
Don't worry about me.
Worry about yourself.

372
00:48:07,510 --> 00:48:09,928
Waking me up
in the middle of the night.

373
00:48:10,013 --> 00:48:11,305
- Ouch!
- What's the matter?

374
00:48:11,389 --> 00:48:14,850
Doesn't matter.
I could take you with one hand.

375
00:48:17,896 --> 00:48:20,606
- How are you?
- Fine. How are you?

376
00:48:20,690 --> 00:48:23,567
- You look terrific.
- You look terrific.

377
00:48:24,903 --> 00:48:29,573
- What happened?
- A lousy bottle of Mouton broke on me.

378
00:48:29,657 --> 00:48:31,742
Hey, get some glasses.

379
00:48:31,826 --> 00:48:35,537
Do I have to hear a lecture
on the glories of a Burgundy again?

380
00:48:35,622 --> 00:48:40,584
This is a Beaujolais, schmuck.
Moulin-‡-Vent, '71.

381
00:48:41,503 --> 00:48:42,503
(SIGHS)

382
00:48:42,587 --> 00:48:46,131
Don't you ever
clean this armpit of a place?

383
00:48:46,382 --> 00:48:48,175
How can you live like this?

384
00:48:48,259 --> 00:48:49,843
I'm down in Washington.

385
00:48:49,928 --> 00:48:52,971
- Here we go.
- I can put you up. Go to Georgetown.

386
00:48:53,056 --> 00:48:54,765
No, thank you, but I prefer my hovel.

387
00:48:54,849 --> 00:48:56,934
- I'll do it.
- Thanks.

388
00:48:57,018 --> 00:48:58,519
You did it, huh?

389
00:48:59,187 --> 00:49:02,064
- You really are uncouth.
- You wanted glasses.

390
00:49:02,148 --> 00:49:05,359
You didn't say they needed
to be clean, asshole.

391
00:49:05,860 --> 00:49:08,195
So, how's business?

392
00:49:10,031 --> 00:49:14,118
- The oil business is always good.
- Just a bunch of polluters and thieves.

393
00:49:14,202 --> 00:49:15,369
It's a crazy world.

394
00:49:15,453 --> 00:49:17,454
Any way you can skin it
is your business.

395
00:49:17,539 --> 00:49:19,164
- Cheers.
- Up yours.

396
00:49:21,501 --> 00:49:23,127
- (GARGLES)
- (SCOFFS)

397
00:49:23,211 --> 00:49:26,630
- Irmgard must love your style.
- We don't drink this shit.

398
00:49:28,967 --> 00:49:32,094
- What happened in the park?
- Exactly what I wrote you.

399
00:49:32,428 --> 00:49:33,887
- How many?
- Two.

400
00:49:34,097 --> 00:49:37,683
- Kids?
- They were more like businessmen.

401
00:49:37,934 --> 00:49:41,395
They looked like you. They had suits on.

402
00:49:43,398 --> 00:49:45,941
What's this?
More bullshit for your thesis?

403
00:49:46,025 --> 00:49:48,777
Some interviews about Dad. Read them.

404
00:49:48,903 --> 00:49:50,696
Not interested.

405
00:49:50,780 --> 00:49:52,364
I just want you to read it.

406
00:49:52,448 --> 00:49:55,701
Face it. The old man is dead.
He was a drunk. He killed himself.

407
00:49:55,785 --> 00:49:59,163
He didn't start to drink
till after the hearings.

408
00:49:59,247 --> 00:50:00,706
I got it from his friends.

409
00:50:00,790 --> 00:50:04,084
- Where were those people then?
- They were afraid.

410
00:50:04,169 --> 00:50:07,337
- You're throwing your life away.
- I don't think so.

411
00:50:07,422 --> 00:50:09,006
Nothing you write will change that!

412
00:50:09,090 --> 00:50:12,092
- Give me the courtesy to read it!
- It's over! Forget it!

413
00:50:14,345 --> 00:50:15,721
Maybe for you.

414
00:50:27,817 --> 00:50:31,403
Do you want me to become
a corporate hustler like you?

415
00:50:33,448 --> 00:50:37,117
- My life's thrown away, anyway.
- What do you mean?

416
00:50:38,077 --> 00:50:40,204
I'm supposed to be
the best in my business.

417
00:50:40,288 --> 00:50:42,623
I'm the best because
people think I am the best.

418
00:50:43,917 --> 00:50:47,252
I'm past it. I know it.
Soon it'll become common knowledge.

419
00:50:48,963 --> 00:50:50,964
Boy, something has gotten you.

420
00:50:52,634 --> 00:50:53,884
Babe...

421
00:50:57,889 --> 00:51:00,682
I bet you still have that goddamn gun.

422
00:51:12,028 --> 00:51:13,487
Why do you keep it?

423
00:51:16,991 --> 00:51:18,367
I don't know.

424
00:51:22,705 --> 00:51:26,792
For a liberal pacifist,
you've got some sense of vengeance.

425
00:51:27,126 --> 00:51:29,419
Is Helga as morbid as you?

426
00:51:29,712 --> 00:51:33,298
I know you're trying to bait me.
You know her name isn't Helga.

427
00:51:33,383 --> 00:51:36,134
Or Ursula or Irmgard.

428
00:51:36,511 --> 00:51:40,013
- You know what her name is!
- All right, all right.

429
00:51:40,348 --> 00:51:42,933
Can I take you and Elsa
to lunch tomorrow?

430
00:51:43,017 --> 00:51:46,103
- But don't eat with your fingers.
- I promise.

431
00:51:46,187 --> 00:51:47,604
It's a deal.

432
00:51:47,689 --> 00:51:50,607
- Okay, I get the bed.
- Same as always.

433
00:51:50,692 --> 00:51:52,276
You have any clean sheets?

434
00:51:53,695 --> 00:51:55,779
I think I may have one left.

435
00:52:04,998 --> 00:52:07,499
I really wanted to say that...

436
00:52:07,583 --> 00:52:08,625
What?

437
00:52:09,168 --> 00:52:10,294
What?

438
00:52:12,839 --> 00:52:14,298
I'm glad to see you.

439
00:52:17,719 --> 00:52:19,011
Doc?

440
00:52:23,558 --> 00:52:25,559
I'm glad you came down.

441
00:52:31,733 --> 00:52:35,068
- When did you last take a subway?
- About 1962.

442
00:52:35,194 --> 00:52:38,989
Excuse me, sir.
Would you mind putting on this tie?

443
00:52:39,073 --> 00:52:40,365
Why?

444
00:52:40,450 --> 00:52:44,119
It's a rule of the house.
You have to wear a tie here.

445
00:52:44,203 --> 00:52:47,622
- I don't have a button.
- Put it here.

446
00:52:47,832 --> 00:52:50,167
- Would you like me to help?
- BABE: No, I can do it.

447
00:52:50,293 --> 00:52:53,295
- Fine. Thank you very much.
- What a klutz.

448
00:52:53,588 --> 00:52:58,008
- How could you forget a tie?
- Who wears a tie for lunch?

449
00:52:58,092 --> 00:53:00,719
At least his fly is buttoned.

450
00:53:01,679 --> 00:53:04,097
The truffles en croute here
are marvellous.

451
00:53:05,433 --> 00:53:09,186
And if you get hungry,
I'll send the waiter to McDonald's.

452
00:53:09,437 --> 00:53:11,605
- Does it look all right?
- Perfect.

453
00:53:13,816 --> 00:53:17,277
- Number 36, Chablis Grand Cru.
- Yes, sir.

454
00:53:20,448 --> 00:53:24,076
The great Chablis of the world
are almost always green-eyed.

455
00:53:25,745 --> 00:53:29,373
In fact, they're the ones
that most resemble diamonds.

456
00:53:42,261 --> 00:53:44,137
Please, start.

457
00:53:48,059 --> 00:53:49,309
Sir.

458
00:53:50,269 --> 00:53:52,979
- You approve?
- Too much.

459
00:53:53,815 --> 00:53:55,190
- It's delicious.
- It should be.

460
00:53:55,274 --> 00:53:57,651
I could pay my tuition
for what this meal costs.

461
00:53:58,820 --> 00:54:02,489
See the watch he gave me
the last time he was here?

462
00:54:02,907 --> 00:54:04,157
Nice.

463
00:54:05,159 --> 00:54:07,702
Do you miss home? I bet you do.

464
00:54:07,787 --> 00:54:11,998
What do you miss most of all?
The people? The country? Skiing?

465
00:54:13,167 --> 00:54:14,751
ELSA: I suppose all.

466
00:54:14,836 --> 00:54:16,628
DOC: I'm not that familiar
with Switzerland.

467
00:54:17,046 --> 00:54:18,797
What part are you from?

468
00:54:18,881 --> 00:54:21,675
A tiny place. Verbier.

469
00:54:22,760 --> 00:54:23,969
Verbier?

470
00:54:24,554 --> 00:54:26,555
- I don't believe it!
- What?

471
00:54:27,223 --> 00:54:31,393
A guy in my office, a ski bum,
a pain in the ass about skiing.

472
00:54:31,477 --> 00:54:32,436
Excuse me.

473
00:54:32,520 --> 00:54:38,483
He's always going on about Verbier.
Right at the foot of Mount Rosa?

474
00:54:38,568 --> 00:54:41,862
- It's the best skiing in the world. True?
- Of course.

475
00:54:41,946 --> 00:54:44,656
- DOC: Was he 100% right?
- ELSA: Sure.

476
00:54:44,740 --> 00:54:47,033
You must know Claude LeSeur.

477
00:54:47,118 --> 00:54:49,035
- Have you skied with him?
- Yeah!

478
00:54:49,120 --> 00:54:50,120
Where is it?

479
00:54:50,204 --> 00:54:52,205
- Verbier.
- Verbier.

480
00:54:53,958 --> 00:54:55,750
I've made all this up.

481
00:54:56,210 --> 00:55:00,130
There's no Mount Rosa in Verbier
or Claude LeSeur.

482
00:55:00,214 --> 00:55:02,257
You're not Swiss. What are you?

483
00:55:03,551 --> 00:55:04,885
What are you?

484
00:55:05,928 --> 00:55:08,555
- Can't you guess?
- Sure. German.

485
00:55:09,223 --> 00:55:12,559
- ELSA: Anything else?
- How long are your papers good for?

486
00:55:13,394 --> 00:55:16,354
Wait. If this is a joke, it's not funny.

487
00:55:16,439 --> 00:55:19,274
I don't need work papers.
I'm a student here.

488
00:55:20,610 --> 00:55:23,820
Many foreigners marry Americans
to make things legal.

489
00:55:23,905 --> 00:55:26,907
- Then the marriages don't work out.
- Is that what you think of me?

490
00:55:26,991 --> 00:55:28,158
Stop it.

491
00:55:28,242 --> 00:55:31,536
- Ask me if I care for him.
- Why? You haven't told the truth so far.

492
00:55:31,621 --> 00:55:35,165
Why don't you ask me if I love him?
Why don't you...

493
00:55:35,416 --> 00:55:38,251
BABE: Wait a minute. Elsa! Wait!

494
00:55:38,336 --> 00:55:41,630
Let her go. She's a phoney.
She's after something. Can't you see it?

495
00:55:41,714 --> 00:55:43,632
Stay out of it!

496
00:56:18,209 --> 00:56:21,920
- You ordered Scylla to be prompt?
- Ja.

